02:05.622 --> 02:06.845
So why does this make sense?

02:07.205 --> 02:14.038
Because what we would expect from like single tokens, these are not interactions yet, these are not biological functions yet.

02:14.018 --> 02:22.647
So, we know that in the lower layers of a neural network, we have these kind of basic features, basic feature extractors.

02:22.728 --> 02:33.179
And here, these basic feature extractors appear to be simply paying attention to one specific token in the vocabulary a lot.

02:33.339 --> 02:39.486
So, these heads sort of specialize for single amino acids.

02:39.466 --> 02:41.688
And the same in the last layer.

02:41.768 --> 02:50.656
So in the very last layer, the task of the very last layer is to prepare for the classification task.

02:50.676 --> 02:55.220
So if you remember the BERT model, you have layer, layer, layer, layer.

02:55.581 --> 02:59.865
And at the end, you'll have to predict which ones are masked down here.

03:00.365 --> 03:03.528
So at the end, you'll have to predict single amino acids again.

03:03.628 --> 03:09.253
So if there's a proline masked here, you'll have to predict the proline.

03:09.233 --> 03:15.560
So it also makes sense that the last layers would very much specialize to single tokens.

03:16.982 --> 03:18.884
So this does make sense.

03:19.765 --> 03:25.952
Now, our question is going to be, do we find the biological function?

03:26.032 --> 03:27.434
Where would you expect them?

03:27.474 --> 03:38.667
We would expect, let's say, the secondary structures, which are sort of one level higher than the primary structures, we would expect to find them maybe here.

03:38.647 --> 03:44.495
And then we would expect to find the tertiary structures maybe somewhere here, okay?

03:44.535 --> 03:46.665
Because these are most highest level.

03:48.552 --> 03:50.335
And then it goes back again.

03:50.575 --> 03:57.925
Or maybe it's like we find the tertiary structures rather here and here again.

03:58.346 --> 04:02.732
And then in the middle, we'll find the most high-level tertiary structures.

04:02.752 --> 04:04.335
Sorry, yeah, blue secondary.

04:05.056 --> 04:08.801
This drawing is getting too weird.

04:09.702 --> 04:13.528
But there could be multiple scenarios that could fit here.

04:14.149 --> 04:17.293
But until now, it sort of makes sense.

04:17.273 --> 04:26.648
So they do an additional investigation where, as I told you, sometimes you can substitute an amino acid and nothing really happens.

04:27.829 --> 04:31.816
And in fact, this probably happens in you right now.

04:31.876 --> 04:40.690
You probably might have some mutation that changed some amino acid and you don't even realize because it's fine.

04:42.072 --> 04:43.534
No notice.

04:43.514 --> 04:51.185
The biologists can build these matrices of how much you can substitute proteins with each other.

04:51.265 --> 04:57.994
So here you see this Blossom 62 substitution scores, which are very, I guess, very high.

04:58.395 --> 05:07.007
If you can substitute two protein, two amino acids with each other and the effect is negligible.

05:08.810 --> 05:12.175
and it's very low if it's the other way around.

05:13.217 --> 05:18.245
Now this is interesting so far, but you compare this to this matrix right here.

05:19.046 --> 05:21.029
This is the attention similarity.

05:21.069 --> 05:33.990
So what we'll do is for each two amino acids, we take those two attention things, those two attention matrices, and we'll calculate the correlation between the attention matrices.

05:33.970 --> 05:44.748
And our hypothesis is that the more correlated the attention patterns are between the two amino acids, the more likely we are to substitute them.

05:45.168 --> 05:55.185
Because as a direct result of our language model, our language model is reconstructing these things.

05:56.752 --> 06:03.945
Our language model is going to treat, if in natural language it's like a synonym, right?

06:05.167 --> 06:11.619
Our language model is going to treat synonyms very similar to each other because they're synonyms, they can be exchanged.

06:11.900 --> 06:20.295
So a good language model should learn that they are almost the same and therefore the attention pattern is going to be almost the same.

06:20.275 --> 06:31.993
So a high correlation we hypothesize means that the function of the amino acid is similar and therefore we can substitute it easily.

06:32.694 --> 06:40.967
So this here is the matrix of the correlations between each two attention patterns of these amino acid.

06:40.947 --> 06:45.556
